<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=99842271413920></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99842271413920><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=11&mid=99842271413920>RE: Quadkiting</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=11&mid=99842271413920#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Aug 21st 3:38 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Since you didn't post your level or what you already know, I mayt repeat something you know, so just bare with me :) Well, first thing is that the only AE you have till the low 50's that is mana efficient enough is Circle of Force. It is definitely a good idea to get a staff of temperate flux. You can check Graffe (www.graffe.com - a excellent wizard site) or this site for quest info. Fairly easy quest if you get help. The staff has an instant cast right click effect of lowering FR and CR - perfect for pulling because of 0 cast time, and lower FR means CoF sticks better. SoW potions or JBoots are essential, as I'm sure you know.<br><br>That is what you need, here is how you do it: Cast sow, jboots, or tboots, naturally. Best to quad in open areas where adds will be easy to avoid, and you can select your targets. As you are running around, find your targets, and you have a couple options for pulling - Staff of Temperate Flux is by far the best option. Just target and click while running, and find your next target. You can run by and just agro by geting close, but you will more than likely take hits doing this. Use a quickly casting low level dd, but you will likely take hits from your previous pulls as you are pulling more. Finally, you can snare each mob individually. This technique kinda sucks, as you use alot of mana pulling, and will have to resnare once they are together. Not to mention the danger involved in that the mobs are slow moving, which makes them more difficult to pull away from potential adds.<br><br>Ok, so by whatever means, you have pulled your mobs. Now you need to get them to a pretty open area where there are no other mobs. You need to group them together by running arouns them, between them if they are seperated, or running across them. Just running circles around them is generally the best thing to do. Once they are together, run away until they are just out of range of BoF, then stop, and cast right as they enter it's range. Make sure that all are snared. If some resist, run away, an repeat the smae process to snare them. Then round them, all up again and resnare. It is essentiall that all are snared at the same time - BoF wears off right about the same time it takes to kill with CoF, so any unexpected problems can cause you to have a few fast, angry mobs on you. Once all are snared, it's simple. Run, cast, run, cast till dead, just like normal kiting. You will get a feel for how long bonds stays on, and if you think it is about to wear off, be safe and recast it, making sure that its sticks on every mob.<br><br>A few final comments. Kiting 2 at a time is about as mana efficient as just soloing 2 individually, so try to get at least three. It sounds like alot of work by how much I have written, but once you get a feel for it, it is really quite simple, painless, and quick. I cannot stress enough how much easier, safer, and faster a Staff of Temperate Flux makes everything. Get one as soon as you can :) Once you start quadding, you will be absolutely amazed at how fast the exp rolls in. At 45, I could make a blue per quad with low 30's - awesome exp for that lvl. In non hells, I was making as much as nearly 2 blues per quad.<br><br>Have fun, and happy hunting<br><br>Saddil Happy<br>Wizzard follower of Solusek Ro<br>Drinal<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
