<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=9974055151148></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9974055151148><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=11&mid=9974055151148>Starting Wizard</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=11&mid=9974055151148#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Aug 9th 9:05 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>The last few posts are all about starting a new wizard so I'll see what I can cover quickly.&nbsp;&nbsp;Firstly race-the main difference at lower levels is really just infravision, sure there is a bit of intelligence difference (remember to put as many spare points as possible into it) but that doesn't really equal a big mana difference, As a High Elf Wizard (untwinked) I've never had any problems manawise, if you are running short, don't fight that type of creature.  Also root is basically useless until about level 8 minimum, even then I would hesitate.  I didn't really start using root until about level 12+ when I used it to stop runners in the Crushbone throneroom.  It is easy to have a decent AC at this level (Raw Silk is your staple for ages anyway, you can buy it fairly cheaply, but it is easy to skill up to the level needed to tailor it) and you need to build up some weapon skills here, you don't have enough mana to pull your weight properly in a group, and especially if you fight in the Crushbone throneroom, you need to be able to save your mana or even go toe-to-toe with the odd legionaire to help keep everyone alive.  The room is too crowded to sit and med so what else can you do anway, My attack skills were maxed out most of the time, over a long fight that extra few hunded damage you do can meen the difference between life and death.  At this point I must mention that many people don't like tanking their wizards, I love doing it, sure it's risky, but AoE spells can reak massive damage if used well, and if you can sustain a beating rather than running like a headless chicken then all the better.  Plus you will get remembered as being a sensible player, headless chickens do not make good names for themselves.  Note: Tanking above level 20 is really not advised, unfortunatly this is also when you will notice root breaking a lot easier on quite a few mobs.<br><br>The new High Elf wizard should fight the bats, wasps, pawns, pixies etc that are nearby until about level 3 or 4, then you need to get an orc hill group.  Say what you like about the place, but orc hill and crushbone have the best xp and loot (both money and belts) for miles around.  Remember to save your Crushbone Belts, they can be turned into Canloe Nusback in the Kaladim warriors guild for extra xp, money and a piece of leather armor.<br>Right, now that level 6 wizard in WFP should get on a boat to Faydwer and go hunt at Orc Hill.  It really is the best, and easiest experiance, plus you can make lots of friends, which makes grouping easier later.  After a few more levels, you can move onto Crushbone, you can really stay here until about level 17 or even higher, but if you are anything like me then you will get sick of it long before then.  The best xp I have found at level 16 and maybe 15 are some sirens in the Ocean of Tears, bind yourself on the Butcherblock docks, catch the Freeport boat and jump off at the first set of rocks, there are two sirens, you could probably even take these 2 at level 15 but at 16 the experiance is unbelievable.  I didn't die once camping these all through 16, just pull them from the nearby island with you bolt spell.  Remember, you can't hit them when they are in the water, cast root so it catches them just as they hop onto your island and then blast.  They go down really easily )<br><br>Finally the latest post, www.graffe.com is a great wizard compendium, they message boards there are populated by heaps of very helpful wizards.  Also Castorsrealm has an area where people post strategies on what to do at certain levels.  As for specialisation, don't worry about it until level 16 ( I think, maybe it's 20 ), you don't get the skill until then.  You train one point into each field of magic, conjuration, evocation etc.  Just as with your regular skills, your specialisation skills will slowly go up.  The higher they are the better chance you have to cast a spell using less mana than it normally takes (there may also be another benefit, not sure).  Now only one field of magic can go above 50 points, naturally you will want to choose evocation, you don't really have to worry much, ecovation spells no doubt outnumber your regular spells 5:1 so you will find it shoots past 50 before you other skills even approach 30.<br><br>Anyway I hope this helps clear up some questions, if you are on the Zebuxoruk server feel free to send me a tell.  I'll help out with any information I can but don't bother asking for money, I'm permanantly broke.  Smithing is hideously expensive, but I want my Cultural Armor )<br><br>Macfudd<br>High Elf Wizard<br>Level 23<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
